AGI - Several people were "gravely wounded" in a knife attack in the German city of Mannheim, said head of government Olaf Scholz, who spoke of "horrible" images. "My thoughts are for the victims," wrote Scholz on X. "Violence is absolutely unacceptable in our democracy. The manager must be severely punished," he added.
&nbsp;
Among the wounded, in addition to the attacker, there are a police officer and an anti-Islam activist who was preparing to participate in a demonstration of his movement. The police didn't give any more details, just saying that several people were wounded in a knife attack and that the agents shot and wounded the attacker.
&nbsp;
The images published on social media show a young armed knife stabbing different people in the center of Mannheim. Several men try to block him on the ground, without success. The attacker managed to get up and hit a cop in the back, before another agent stopped him by shooting him.<br> According to several media, including the Bild newspaper, the main target of the attack was Michael Sturzenberger, a well-known anti-Islam activist, who was about to speak at a meeting organized by the Pax Europa Citizens' Movement (BPE). This movement, whose goal is to denounce "the dangers of the influence of political Islam on democratic societies in Germany and Europe", reported the attack on Sturzenberger on his website, referring to a "knife attack" during one of his meetings.
&nbsp;
The activist, as well as "advertent BPE volunteers and a cop were stabbed", some in a "grave" way, declared the movement. According to BPE, the cop was wounded in the back and back. Sturzenberger, 59, is a former spokesman of the Bavarian Conservative Party CSU in Monaco and is active in several organizations close to the extreme right.&nbsp;

